docs.abstract: When demonstrators dumped the monument to a slave trader into Bristol Harbor, they galvanized a debate that echoes conversations happening in the American South about statues of Confederate generals.
docs.snippet: When demonstrators dumped the monument to a slave trader into Bristol Harbor, they galvanized a debate that echoes conversations happening in the American South about statues of Confederate generals.
docs.lead_paragraph: LONDON — With a mix of pent-up fury and sudden elation, the protesters who toppled a bronze statue of the 17th-century slave trader Edward Colston in Bristol, England, on Sunday recalled the angry crowds that brought down statues of Saddam Hussein, Stalin and even King George III.

headline.main: ‘Get Rid of Them’: A Statue Falls as Britain Confronts Its Racist History
headline.print_headline: ‘Get Rid of Them’: A Statue Falls as Britain Confronts History of Racism

docs.abstract: A heated dispute between the newsroom and the opinion section of one of the country’s most respected news organizations has spilled into public view.
docs.snippet: A heated dispute between the newsroom and the opinion section of one of the country’s most respected news organizations has spilled into public view.
docs.lead_paragraph: In a rare display of internal strife, the opinion department of The Wall Street Journal openly antagonized the paper’s news staff Thursday by publishing a tersely worded note to readers just days after it found itself on the receiving end of a sharply worded critique signed by hundreds of newsroom employees.

headline.main: At Wall Street Journal, News Staff and Opinion Side Clash
headline.print_headline: News and Opinion Clash at Wall Street Journal

docs.abstract: It won’t be easy, but our democracy depends on it.
docs.snippet: It won’t be easy, but our democracy depends on it.
docs.lead_paragraph: The same information revolution that brought us Netflix, podcasts and the knowledge of the world in our smartphone-gripping hands has also undermined American democracy. There can be no doubt that virally spread political disinformation and delusional invective about stolen, rigged elections are threatening the foundation of our Republic. It’s going to take both legal and political change to bolster that foundation, and it might not be enough.

headline.main: How to Keep the Rising Tide of Fake News From Drowning Our Democracy

docs.abstract: Where his older brother, Nawaz Sharif, has been criticized for a low-energy style in power, Shehbaz Sharif has nurtured a nearly opposite reputation.
docs.snippet: Where his older brother, Nawaz Sharif, has been criticized for a low-energy style in power, Shehbaz Sharif has nurtured a nearly opposite reputation.
docs.lead_paragraph: ISLAMABAD, Pakistan — With his term as Pakistan’s prime minister cut short, and with his governing party facing critical national elections in less than a year, Nawaz Sharif announced publicly on Saturday that he was choosing his younger brother, Shehbaz Sharif, to be his long-term replacement as prime minister and as the party’s standard bearer.

headline.main: Ousted Pakistan Leader Passes Baton to Brother, Shehbaz Sharif
headline.print_headline: Term as Pakistan Premier Cut Short, Sharif Passes Baton to Brother

docs.abstract: The police said an attack on the pianist was not a hate crime, but social media disagreed. Now he’s considering a return to Japan.
docs.snippet: The police said an attack on the pianist was not a hate crime, but social media disagreed. Now he’s considering a return to Japan.
docs.lead_paragraph: He came to New York from Tokyo to make it as a jazz musician, and he did, landing gigs in several touring bands and leading a trio of his own. He was elegant but never flashy on the piano, always well prepared and on time.

headline.main: He Was a Rising Jazz Pianist. Then His N.Y.C. Dreams Were Shattered.

docs.abstract: A new comedy by Steph Del Rosso starts as a satire of conservatives, then takes aim at progressives. Too bad the jokes barely cut either side.
docs.snippet: A new comedy by Steph Del Rosso starts as a satire of conservatives, then takes aim at progressives. Too bad the jokes barely cut either side.
docs.lead_paragraph: In America, to vote in a federal election is to commit a secret act. One votes in private, in a curtained booth, on intimate terms with an oversize ballot. But little in American public life stays private for long.

headline.main: ‘53% Of’ Review: Zinging Pro-Trump Women, and Everyone Else

docs.abstract: Less than a year after Larry Nassar’s sentencing, decisions by U.S.A. Gymnastics created a backlash among athletes that has left the federation teetering.
docs.snippet: Less than a year after Larry Nassar’s sentencing, decisions by U.S.A. Gymnastics created a backlash among athletes that has left the federation teetering.
docs.lead_paragraph: America’s best gymnasts have shaken their heads for years at the failure of their national federation to understand the blighted culture of their sport, one that allowed a team doctor to abuse them for decades while the sport’s leaders looked the other way.

headline.main: ‘Seriously, You Chose Her?’: U.S.A. Gymnastics’ Trouble at the Top
headline.print_headline: At U.S.A. Gymnastics, a History of Letting Down Its Athletes

docs.abstract: President Trump told suburban voters that affordable housing would hurt property values and increase crime. The story of one Wisconsin community challenges those assumptions.
docs.snippet: President Trump told suburban voters that affordable housing would hurt property values and increase crime. The story of one Wisconsin community challenges those assumptions.
docs.lead_paragraph: NEW BERLIN, Wis. — When John Blaguski first heard about a proposal to build an affordable housing complex near his home in the Milwaukee suburb of New Berlin, Wis., his mind drifted to stereotypes of crime-ridden, shoddily constructed projects.

headline.main: Residents Feared Low-Income Housing Would Ruin Their Suburb. It Didn’t.

docs.abstract: Our columnists and contributors give their rankings.
docs.snippet: Our columnists and contributors give their rankings.
docs.lead_paragraph: Welcome to Opinion’s commentary for the last night of the Republican National Convention. In this special feature, Times Opinion writers rank the evening on a scale of 1 to 10: 1 means the night was a disaster for Republicans; 10 means it could lead to a big polling bump for the Trump-Pence ticket. Here’s what our columnists and contributors thought of the event, which featured Ivanka Trump and President Trump himself.

headline.main: Republican Convention: Best and Worst Moments From Trump’s Big Night
